+Please implement this: The "invisible margin" you are experiencing is actually the bounding box of the text element itself! 
+
+In the previous configuration, new text items were being added with an artificial width constraint (`width: canvasWidth - 100`) and placed at `x: 50`. Because the Konva `<Text>` component uses this `width` as a hard boundary, increasing the font size caused the text to hit that invisible 284px box and wrap/clip, rather than utilizing the full 384px print area.
+
+Here are the fixes to ensure you can utilize every single pixel from edge to red-dashed-edge.
+
+### 1. Make New Text Span the Full Canvas by Default
+We will remove the artificial width constraint so new text items start at `X: 0` and span the absolute full width of the printable area.
+
+**File:** `frontend/src/components/Sidebar.jsx`
+Find the `handleAddText` function and update the `x` and `width` values:
+
+```javascript
+  const handleAddText = () => {
+    addItem({
+      id: Date.now().toString(),
+      type: 'text',
+      text: 'Double click to edit',
+      x: 0,                    // <-- Changed from 50 to 0 (Left edge)
+      y: 50,
+      size: 24,
+      font: 'arial.ttf',
+      width: canvasWidth,      // <-- Changed from canvasWidth - 100 (Full width)
+      align: 'center'
+    });
+  };
+```
+
+### 2. Add a "Full Width" Snap Button & Improve Font Measurement
+If you have an existing text block that has been dragged or resized, you need an easy way to snap it back to the absolute edges. We'll add a "Full Width" button next to the centering tools, and we'll also apply the chosen font family to the browser's width estimation.
+
+**File:** `frontend/src/components/PropertiesPanel.jsx`
+Update the `handleFitToWidth` function and add the `handleMakeFullWidth` function:
+
+```javascript
+  const handleCenterH = () => {
+    const itemW = selectedItem.width || 0;
+    updateItem(selectedId, { x: (canvasWidth - itemW) / 2 });
+  };
+
+  const handleCenterV = () => {
+    const itemH = selectedItem.height || (selectedItem.type === 'text' ? selectedItem.size : 0);
+    updateItem(selectedId, { y: (canvasHeight - itemH) / 2 });
+  };
+
+  // NEW: Instantly snap text box to the absolute red boundaries
+  const handleMakeFullWidth = () => {
+    updateItem(selectedId, { x: 0, width: canvasWidth });
+  };
+
+  // ... [skip handleChange] ...
+
+  const handleFitToWidth = () => {
+    if (!selectedItem.width || !selectedItem.text) return;
+    
+    const canvas = document.createElement('canvas');
+    const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
+    const fontFamily = selectedItem.font ? selectedItem.font.split('.')[0] : 'Arial';
+    
+    let low = 6;
+    let high = 800;
+    let bestSize = selectedItem.size;
+    const targetWidth = selectedItem.width; 
+
+    while (low <= high) {
+      let mid = Math.floor((low + high) / 2);
+      ctx.font = `${mid}px ${fontFamily}`; // Include font family for better browser estimation
+      let textWidth = ctx.measureText(selectedItem.text.split('\n')[0]).width;
+      
+      if (textWidth <= targetWidth) {
+        bestSize = mid;
+        low = mid + 1;
+      } else {
+        high = mid - 1;
+      }
+    }
+    
+    updateItem(selectedId, { size: bestSize, no_wrap: true, fit_to_width: true });
+  };
+```
+
+Further down in the same `PropertiesPanel.jsx` file, add the new button to your UI inside the positioning div:
+
+```javascript
+          <div className="flex gap-4">
+            <ScrubberInput name="x" label="X Pos" value={Math.round(selectedItem.x)} onChange={handleChange} />
+            <ScrubberInput name="y" label="Y Pos" value={Math.round(selectedItem.y)} onChange={handleChange} />
+          </div>
+          <div className="flex gap-2 mt-2">
+            <button onClick={handleCenterH} className="flex-1 bg-neutral-100 dark:bg-neutral-900 text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400 py-1.5 text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest hover:bg-neutral-200 dark:hover:bg-neutral-800 transition-colors">Center H</button>
+            <button onClick={handleCenterV} className="flex-1 bg-neutral-100 dark:bg-neutral-900 text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400 py-1.5 text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest hover:bg-neutral-200 dark:hover:bg-neutral-800 transition-colors">Center V</button>
+            
+            {/* NEW BUTTON */}
+            <button onClick={handleMakeFullWidth} className="flex-1 bg-neutral-100 dark:bg-neutral-900 text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400 py-1.5 text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest hover:bg-neutral-200 dark:hover:bg-neutral-800 transition-colors">Full Width</button>
+          </div>
+```
+
+### 3. Pass FontFamily to the Canvas Element
+To make the frontend editor match the backend output as closely as possible, we should pass the parsed font name into the Konva `<Text />` component.
+
+**File:** `frontend/src/components/CanvasArea.jsx`
+Find the `item.type === 'text'` condition inside the `.map()` loop and update it to use `fontFamily`:
+
+```javascript
+                if (item.type === 'text') {
+                  const fontFamily = item.font ? item.font.split('.')[0] : 'Arial';
+                  return <Text 
+                    {...commonProps} 
+                    text={item.text} 
+                    align={item.align || 'left'} 
+                    fontFamily={fontFamily} 
+                    wrap={item.no_wrap ? "none" : "word"} 
+                    fontSize={item.size} 
+                    fill={isSelected ? '#2563eb' : 'black'} 
+                    padding={0} 
+                  />;
+                }
+```
+
+### Summary of what this does:
+1. When you click "+ Add Text", it now creates a bounding box exactly 384px wide starting exactly at `X: 0`.
+2. Because the bounding box touches the red dashed lines, clicking **Maximize Font to Width** will calculate the font size against the full 48mm / 384px area. 
+3. If an element gets accidentally resized or dragged, clicking **Full Width** instantly restores its bounding box to cover the entirety of the printable area.

